b'' b'|' b'| the shell is waiting for the window-manager to respond to its' b'| positioning request. the window-manager is not responding because' b'| it thinks the window is already in the right place.' b'|' b'| exactly *why* the two components get into this sulk is unclear to' b'| me; all information greatly received.' b'' b'this problem is caused by a bad interaction between the way olwm reparents' b'windows, a misfeature of the x protocol, and a bug in the xt intrinsics.' b'' b'the intrinsics bug is that it ignores the (x,y) position given in' b'reparentnotify events. olwm is structured in such a way that, when a window' b'is popped down, the last event the client receives is a reparentnotify event.' b"at this point, the intrinsics' notion of the shell's location is out of date." b'' b'if a setvalues is done using the same (x,y) position, the intrinsics thinks it' b'needs to move the shell, so it issues a configurewindow request to move it' b'there. however, a (mis)feature of the x protocol is that a configurewindow' b'request that has no effect will generate no configurenotify event. the' b'intrinsics thus waits for an event that will never arrive, and times out after' b'wmtimeout has expired. (actually, things are somewhat more complex because' b'the request is redirected to the window manager, but the net result is the' b'same.)' b'' b'the solution is for the intrinsics to note the (x,y) positioning information' b'in reparentnotify events. this has been implemented and is available in x11r5' b'public fix this is xbug for those of you who are interested in' b'gorier details.' b'' b"s'marks" b'' b'--' b'window systems technology\t\t2550 garcia ave. m/s b'sunsoft, inc.\t\t\t\tmountain view, ca 